    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "The 'Test samples' factor in ASME V&V 40 addresses variability arising from biological specimen-to-specimen variation when physical tissue or patient samples are used in validation experiments. In this assessment, validation experiments use a synthetic blood analog fluid (glycerol-water solution with matched viscosity) prepared from reagent-grade materials under controlled conditions. No biological donor samples, harvested tissue, or patient-derived specimens are involved. Specimen-to-specimen biological variability is therefore absent by design, and the factor has no meaningful scope within this COU. The fluid property characterization is captured under the Model Inputs factor."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "The 'Equivalency of input parameters' factor applies when validation experiments are conducted on a surrogate or scaled geometry that differs from the clinical device, requiring a formal demonstration that the input parameter space of the surrogate maps equivalently to the COU device. In this assessment, validation experiments were performed on the identical FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry used in the COU, confirmed by coordinate measuring machine (CMM) inspection to within ±0.05 mm manufacturing tolerances. No surrogate geometry, scaled model, or analogue device was employed. Because the validation and COU geometries are the same physical configuration, there is no parameter equivalency gap to bridge, and this factor does not apply."
    }
